    <title>Changing the MTU on a small-footprint System using the CLI</title>
    <shortdesc>
        <draft-comment author="rstone">Topic created for CGTS-1944</draft-comment>
    </shortdesc>
    <prolog><author/>
        <author>Ron Stone</author>
    </prolog>
    <body>
        
            <p>The following steps illustrate how to change the MTU for an interface
                for an infrastructure network. This example uses eth6 as the interface to be
                changed.</p>
        
        <ol>
             
                <li>Lock controller-1.
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-lock controller-1</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Modify the MTU of an interface on controller-1.
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-if-modify controller-1 eth6 --imtu 1600</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Unlock controller-1.
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-unlock controller-1</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Swact the host to controller-1. 
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-swact controller-1</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Lock controller-0.
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-lock controller-0</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Modify the MTU of the interface on controller-0. 
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-if-modify controller-0 eth6 --imtu 1600</codeblock>
                
                </li>
             
                <li>Unlock controller-0. 
                
                    <codeblock>~(keystone_admin)$ system host-unlock controller-0</codeblock>
                </li>
            
        </ol>
    </body>
